class Solution {
    public int findChampion(int n, int[][] edges) {
        int[] degree = new int[n];
        for (int[] e : edges) {
            degree[e[1]]++;
        }
        int champion = -1;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if (degree[i] == 0) {
                if (champion == -1) {
                    champion = i;
                } else {
                    return -1;
                }
            }
        }
        return champion;
    }
}

A: The key to solving this problem is to realize that a leaf node cannot be part of a path that sums to 0, as it would not have any siblings to balance the loss. Therefore, we can traverse the tree in a depth-first manner, and for each node, calculate the sum of the values of its children. We then take the minimum of the node's value and the sum of its children's values, as this represents the minimum loss that can be achieved at that node. We then recursively calculate the minimum loss for each child node, and add up the minimum losses of all children to obtain the maximum possible score.
