class Solution {
    public long maximumScoreAfterOperations(int[][] edges, int[] values) {
        List<Integer>[] g = new ArrayList[values.length];
        Arrays.setAll(g, e -> new ArrayList<>());
        g[0].add(-1); // add a dummy parent for the root node
        for (int[] e : edges) {
            int x = e[0], y = e[1];
            g[x].add(y);
            g[y].add(x);
        }
        long ans = 0;
        for (int v : values) {
            ans += v;
        }
        return ans - dfs(0, -1, g, values);
    }

    private long dfs(int x, int fa, List<Integer>[] g, int[] values) {
        if (g[x].size() == 1) { // leaf node
            return values[x];
        }
        long loss = 0;
        for (int y : g[x]) {
            if (y != fa) {
                loss += dfs(y, x, g, values);
            }
        }
        return Math.min(values[x], loss);
    }
}

In this solution, the dfs function is a recursive function that takes four arguments: x is the current node being visited, fa is the parent node of x, g is the adjacency list representation of the tree, and values is the array of node values. The function returns the minimum loss that can be achieved at node x.

